1. Metadata & “Derived Data” Laws (Often Overlooked)

Even if you do not store audio, regulators may still ask about:

A. Derived / Inferred Data

Some laws treat processed signals as data even if raw input is discarded.

Examples:

Frequency values

Amplitude levels

Timing patterns

Behavioral inference (e.g., “mood,” “state,” “attention”)

Risk Mitigation (what to add or confirm)

You already do most of this, but ensure you explicitly state:

No frequency data is saved

No behavioral profile is created

No persistent state tied to a user/session

No inference is exported or retained

Why it matters:
Certain privacy frameworks define “personal data” to include inferences, not just raw input.

2. State Privacy Laws Beyond Audio Consent

Even without recording, some states regulate interactive software behavior.

A. State Consumer Privacy Acts (U.S.)

Examples (non-exhaustive):

California

Colorado

Virginia

Connecticut

Utah

Common themes:

Right to know what data is processed

Right to opt out of certain processing

Prohibition on misleading disclosures

What to do

Your current wording already helps, but best practice is to include:

“No personal data is sold, shared, or retained”

“No profiling for commercial purposes”

“No cross-site tracking”

3. Biometric & Voice Laws (Even If You Don’t Record)

Some laws define biometrics broadly.

Risk Areas

Voice characteristics

Behavioral signals tied to a person

“Unique identifiers” inferred from sound

Why You’re Likely Safe

You:

Don’t store voiceprints

Don’t identify users

Don’t authenticate by voice

Still Recommended Disclosure

Add or keep:

“This software does not perform biometric identification, authentication, or recognition.”

4. Health & Wellness Data Laws (Indirect Risk)

Because your project references:

“mood”

“state”

“awareness”

Some regulators may ask whether it:

Diagnoses

Monitors mental state

Provides health insights

Strong Protection (already mostly done)

You should explicitly state:

No medical or psychological claims

No health diagnosis

No wellness tracking

No treatment or recommendation

Why:
Health-related data triggers stricter obligations even if accidental.

5. Deceptive Design / Dark Pattern Laws

Modern enforcement increasingly targets UI behavior, not just data.

What They Look For

Hidden consent

Ambiguous buttons

Surprise microphone activation

UI that nudges users into enabling sensors

Your Fixes (Good)

Explicit button to start audio

Clear text disclosures

No auto-start mic

Extra Line You Can Add

“Microphone access is always user-initiated and never enabled automatically.”

6. Accessibility Laws (Legal, Not Just Ethical)

Accessibility is legally enforced, not optional.

Applies Under:

Disability discrimination laws

Public accommodation standards

Government procurement rules (if ever used)

What You Already Did Right

Keyboard access

Screen-reader support

Reduced motion support

Text alternatives

One More Protective Statement

“This interface is designed to be usable with keyboard navigation and assistive technologies.”

7. Intellectual Property & Content Liability

Even if code is yours, visuals and language matter.

Risks

Background images

Fonts

Third-party libraries

Generated text misattributed

Mitigation

Confirm you have rights to images

Avoid implying third-party endorsement

Keep AI assistance disclosure (you already do)

8. Export Control (Low Probability, High Impact)

This matters only if you later add:

Encryption

Advanced sensing

Autonomous decision-making

Cross-border distribution

What to Say Now

A simple disclaimer is enough:

“This project is not designed for regulated export use.”

9. Future Feature Drift (Biggest Real Risk)

Most compliance problems arise when features change but disclosures don’t.

High-Risk Additions

If you add ANY of the following, you must update disclosures:

Saving visuals

Session memory

User accounts

Cloud sync

Analytics

Sharing/export

AI models trained on user input

Best Practice (Recommended)

Add a standing notice like:

“If future versions introduce data storage, transmission, accounts, or analytics, disclosures will be updated accordingly.”

10. What You Do NOT Need (Based on Current Design)

You do not currently need:

Cookie banners (if no cookies)

Opt-out links (no data retention)

Data deletion portals (nothing stored)

Age verification (general audience + no collection)

Breach notification language (no retained data)

✅ Minimal “Extra” Lines You Could Add (Optional but Strong)

If you want maximum legal defensiveness with minimal clutter, add these 3 sentences somewhere in your disclosures:

“This software does not perform biometric identification, authentication, or profiling.”

“No behavioral, health, or psychological assessment is performed or implied.”

“All microphone access is user-initiated, session-only, and non-persistent.”

Bottom Line (Plain English)

Your biggest remaining risks are not audio recording—they are:

metadata interpretation

inference claims

UI consent clarity

future feature creep

